# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: parallel-coordinates
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:parallel-coordinates/andrews-plot] In data visualization, an **Andrews plot** or **Andrews curve** is a way to visualize structure in high-dimensional data.
[src:parallel-coordinates/andrews-plot] It is basically a rolled-down, non-integer version of the Kent–Kiviat radar m chart, or a smoothed version of a parallel coordinate plot.
[src:parallel-coordinates/andrews-plot] It is named after the statistician David F.
[src:parallel-coordinates/andrews-plot] A value x is a high-dimensional datapoint if it is an element of $\mathbb {R} ^{d}$ .
[src:parallel-coordinates/andrews-plot] We can represent high-dimensional data with a number for each of their dimensions, $x=\left\{x_{1},x_{2},\ldots ,x_{d}\right\}$ .
[src:parallel-coordinates/andrews-plot] This function is then plotted for $-\pi <t<\pi$ .
[src:parallel-coordinates/andrews-plot] Thus each data point may be viewed as a line between $-\pi$ and $\pi$ .
[src:parallel-coordinates/andrews-plot] If there is structure in the data, it may be visible in the Andrews curves of the data.
[src:parallel-coordinates/andrews-plot] These curves have been utilized in fields as different as biology, neurology, sociology and semiconductor manufacturing.
[src:parallel-coordinates/andrews-plot] Some of their uses include the quality control of products, the detection of period and outliers in time series, the visualization of learning in artificial neural networks, and correspondence analysis.
[src:parallel-coordinates/andrews-plot] Theoretically, it is possible to project them onto an *n*-sphere.
[src:parallel-coordinates/andrews-plot] The projection onto the circle results in the aforementioned radar chart.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] Methods are commonly divided into linear and nonlinear approaches.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] Linear approaches can be further divided into feature selection and feature extraction.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] Dimensionality reduction can be used for noise reduction, data visualization, cluster analysis, or as an intermediate step to facilitate other analyses.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] The process of feature selection aims to find a suitable subset of the input variables (*features*, or *attributes*) for the task at hand.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] The three strategies are: the *filter* strategy (e.g., information gain), the *wrapper* strategy (e.g., accuracy-guided search), and the *embedded* strategy (features are added or removed while building the model based on prediction errors).
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] Data analysis such as regression or classification can be done in the reduced space more accurately than in the original space.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] Feature projection (also called feature extraction) transforms the data from the high-dimensional space to a space of fewer dimensions.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] The data transformation may be linear, as in principal component analysis (PCA), but many nonlinear dimensionality reduction techniques also exist.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] For multidimensional data, tensor representation can be used in dimensionality reduction through multilinear subspace learning.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] The main linear technique for dimensionality reduction, principal component analysis, performs a linear mapping of the data to a lower-dimensional space in such a way that the variance of the data in the low-dimensional representation is maximized.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] In practice, the covariance (and sometimes the correlation) matrix of the data is constructed and the eigenvectors on this matrix are computed.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] The eigenvectors that correspond to the largest eigenvalues (the principal components) can now be used to reconstruct a large fraction of the variance of the original data.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] Moreover, the first few eigenvectors can often be interpreted in terms of the large-scale physical behavior of the system, because they often contribute the vast majority of the system's energy, especially in low-dimensional systems.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] Still, this must be proved on a case-by-case basis as not all systems exhibit this behavior.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] The original space (with dimension of the number of points) has been reduced (with data loss, but hopefully retaining the most important variance) to the space spanned by a few eigenvectors.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] NMF decomposes a non-negative matrix to the product of two non-negative ones, which has been a promising tool in fields where only non-negative signals exist, such as astronomy.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] With a stable component basis during construction, and a linear modeling process, sequential NMF is able to preserve the flux in direct imaging of circumstellar structures in astronomy, as one of the methods of detecting exoplanets, especially for the direct imaging of circumstellar discs.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] In comparison with PCA, NMF does not remove the mean of the matrices, which leads to physical non-negative fluxes; therefore NMF is able to preserve more information than PCA as demonstrated by Ren et al.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] Principal component analysis can be employed in a nonlinear way by means of the kernel trick.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is capable of constructing nonlinear mappings that maximize the variance in the data.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] The resulting technique is called kernel PCA.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] Other prominent nonlinear techniques include manifold learning techniques such as Isomap, locally linear embedding (LLE), Hessian LLE, Laplacian eigenmaps, and methods based on tangent space analysis.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] More recently, techniques have been proposed that, instead of defining a fixed kernel, try to learn the kernel using semidefinite programming.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] The most prominent example of such a technique is maximum variance unfolding (MVU).
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] The central idea of MVU is to exactly preserve all pairwise distances between nearest neighbors (in the inner product space) while maximizing the distances between points that are not nearest neighbors.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] An alternative approach to neighborhood preservation is through the minimization of a cost function that measures differences between distances in the input and output spaces.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] A different approach to nonlinear dimensionality reduction is through the use of autoencoders, a special kind of feedforward neural networks with a bottleneck hidden layer.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] The training of deep encoders is typically performed using a greedy layer-wise pre-training (e.g., using a stack of restricted Boltzmann machines) that is followed by a finetuning stage based on backpropagation.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] Linear discriminant analysis (LDA) is a generalization of Fisher's linear discriminant, a method used in statistics, pattern recognition, and machine learning to find a linear combination of features that characterizes or separates two or more classes of objects or events.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] GDA deals with nonlinear discriminant analysis using kernel function operator.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] The underlying theory is close to the support-vector machines (SVM) insofar as the GDA method provides a mapping of the input vectors into high-dimensional feature space.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] Similar to LDA, the objective of GDA is to find a projection for the features into a lower dimensional space by maximizing the ratio of between-class scatter to within-class scatter.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] Autoencoders can be used to learn nonlinear dimension reduction functions and codings together with an inverse function from the coding to the original representation.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] T-distributed Stochastic Neighbor Embedding (t-SNE) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique useful for the visualization of high-dimensional datasets.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] It is not recommended for use in analysis such as clustering or outlier detection since it does not necessarily preserve densities or distances well.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] Uniform manifold approximation and projection (UMAP) is a nonlinear dimensionality reduction technique.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] Visually, it is similar to t-SNE, but it assumes that the data is uniformly distributed on a locally connected Riemannian manifold and that the Riemannian metric is locally constant or approximately locally constant.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] For high-dimensional datasets, dimension reduction is usually performed prior to applying a *k*-nearest neighbors (*k*-NN) algorithm in order to mitigate the curse of dimensionality.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] In machine learning, this process is also called low-dimensional embedding.
[src:parallel-coordinates/dimensionality-reduction] A dimensionality reduction technique that is sometimes used in neuroscience is maximally informative dimensions, which finds a lower-dimensional representation of a dataset such that as much information as possible about the original data is preserved.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] More technically, MDS refers to a set of related ordination techniques used in information visualization, in particular to display the information contained in a distance matrix.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] It is a form of non-linear dimensionality reduction.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Given a distance matrix with the distances between each pair of objects in a set, and a chosen number of dimensions, *N*, an MDS algorithm places each object into *N*-dimensional space (a lower-dimensional representation) such that the between-object distances are preserved as well as possible.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] For *N* = 1, 2, and 3, the resulting points can be visualized on a scatter plot.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Core theoretical contributions to MDS were made by James O.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Ramsay of McGill University, who is also regarded as the founder of functional data analysis.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] It is also known as **Principal Coordinates Analysis** (PCoA), Torgerson Scaling or Torgerson–Gower scaling.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Determine the ${\textstyle m}$ largest eigenvalues ${\textstyle \lambda _{1},\lambda _{2},...,\lambda _{m}}$ and corresponding eigenvectors ${\textstyle e_{1},e_{2},...,e_{m}}$ of ${\textstyle B}$ (where ${\textstyle m}$ is the number of dimensions desired for the output).
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Now, ${\textstyle X=E_{m}\Lambda _{m}^{1/2}}$ , where ${\textstyle E_{m}}$ is the matrix of ${\textstyle m}$ eigenvectors and ${\textstyle \Lambda _{m}}$ is the diagonal matrix of ${\textstyle m}$ eigenvalues of ${\textstyle B}$ .
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] So this is not applicable for direct dissimilarity ratings.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] It is a superset of classical MDS that generalizes the optimization procedure to a variety of loss functions and input matrices of known distances with weights and so on.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] A useful loss function in this context is called *stress*, which is often minimized using a procedure called stress majorization.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Metric scaling uses a power transformation with a user-controlled exponent ${\textstyle p}$ : ${\textstyle d_{ij}^{p}}$ and ${\textstyle -d_{ij}^{2p}}$ for distance.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] In classical scaling ${\textstyle p=1.}$ Non-metric scaling is defined by the use of isotonic regression to nonparametrically estimate a transformation of the dissimilarities.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] In contrast to metric MDS, non-metric MDS finds both a non-parametric monotonic relationship between the dissimilarities in the item-item matrix and the Euclidean distances between items, and the location of each item in the low-dimensional space.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Let $d_{ij}$ be the dissimilarity between points $i,j$ .
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] The factor of $\sum _{i<j}{\hat {d}}_{ij}^{2}$ in the denominator is necessary to prevent a "collapse".
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Suppose we define instead $S={\sqrt {\sum _{i<j}{\bigl (}f(d_{ij})-{\hat {d}}_{ij})^{2}}}$ , then it can be trivially minimized by setting $f=0$ , then collapse every point to the same point.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] A few variants of this cost function exist.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] MDS programs automatically minimize stress in order to obtain the MDS solution.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] The core of a non-metric MDS algorithm is a twofold optimization process.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] First the optimal monotonic transformation of the proximities has to be found.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Secondly, the points of a configuration have to be optimally arranged, so that their distances match the scaled proximities as closely as possible.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] NMDS needs to optimize two objectives simultaneously.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Louis Guttman's smallest space analysis (SSA) is an example of a non-metric MDS procedure.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] An extension of metric multidimensional scaling, in which the target space is an arbitrary smooth non-Euclidean space.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] In cases where the dissimilarities are distances on a surface and the target space is another surface, GMDS allows finding the minimum-distortion embedding of one surface into another.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] An extension of MDS, known as Super MDS, incorporates both distance and angle information for improved source localization.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Unlike traditional MDS, which uses only distance measurements, Super MDS processes both distance and angle-of-arrival (AOA) data algebraically (without iteration) to achieve better accuracy.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] This concise approach reduces the need for multiple anchors and enhances localization precision by leveraging angle constraints.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] In classical MDS, this norm is the Euclidean distance, but, in a broader sense, it may be a metric or arbitrary distance function.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] For example, when dealing with mixed-type data that contain numerical as well as categorical descriptors, Gower's distance is a common alternative.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] In other words, MDS attempts to find a mapping from the M objects into $\mathbb {R} ^{N}$ such that distances are preserved.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] If the dimension N is chosen to be 2 or 3, we may plot the vectors $x_{i}$ to obtain a visualization of the similarities between the M objects.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Note that the vectors $x_{i}$ are not unique: With the Euclidean distance, they may be arbitrarily translated, rotated, and reflected, since these transformations do not change the pairwise distances $\|x_{i}-x_{j}\|$ .
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] There are various approaches to determining the vectors $x_{i}$ .
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] A solution may then be found by numerical optimization techniques.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] For some particularly chosen cost functions, minimizers can be stated analytically in terms of matrix eigendecompositions.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] **Obtaining input data** – For example, :- Respondents are asked a series of questions.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] For each product pair, they are asked to rate similarity (usually on a 7-point Likert scale from very similar to very dissimilar).
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] The first question could be for Coke/Pepsi for example, the next for Coke/Hires rootbeer, the next for Pepsi/Dr Pepper, the next for Dr Pepper/Hires rootbeer, etc.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] The number of questions is a function of the number of brands and can be calculated as $Q=N(N-1)/2$ where *Q* is the number of questions and *N* is the number of brands.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] This approach is referred to as the “Perception data : direct approach”.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] There is the “Perception data : derived approach” in which products are decomposed into attributes that are rated on a semantic differential scale.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] The other is the “Preference data approach” in which respondents are asked their preference rather than similarity.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] **Running the MDS statistical program** – Software for running the procedure is available in many statistical software packages.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Often there is a choice between Metric MDS (which deals with interval or ratio level data), and Nonmetric MDS (which deals with ordinal data).
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] **Decide number of dimensions** – The researcher must decide on the number of dimensions they want the computer to create.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Interpretability of the MDS solution is often important, and lower dimensional solutions will typically be easier to interpret and visualize.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] However, dimension selection is also an issue of balancing underfitting and overfitting.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Lower dimensional solutions may underfit by leaving out important dimensions of the dissimilarity data.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Higher dimensional solutions may overfit to noise in the dissimilarity measurements.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Model selection tools like AIC, BIC, Bayes factors, or cross-validation can thus be useful to select the dimensionality that balances underfitting and overfitting.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] **Mapping the results and defining the dimensions** – The statistical program (or a related module) will map the results.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] The map will plot each product (usually in two-dimensional space).
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] The proximity of products to each other indicate either how similar they are or how preferred they are, depending on which approach was used.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] How the dimensions of the embedding actually correspond to dimensions of system behavior, however, are not necessarily obvious.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Here, a subjective judgment about the correspondence can be made (see perceptual mapping).
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] **Test the results for reliability and validity** – Compute R-squared to determine what proportion of variance of the scaled data can be accounted for by the MDS procedure.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] An R-square of 0.6 is considered the minimum acceptable level.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] An R-square of 0.8 is considered good for metric scaling and .9 is considered good for non-metric scaling.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] Other possible tests are Kruskal’s Stress, split data tests, data stability tests (i.e., eliminating one brand), and test-retest reliability.
[src:parallel-coordinates/multidimensional-scaling] **Report the results comprehensively** – Along with the mapping, at least distance measure (e.g., Sorenson index, Jaccard index) and reliability (e.g., stress value) should be given.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] To plot, or visualize, a set of points in *n*-dimensional space, *n* parallel lines are drawn over the background representing coordinate axes, typically oriented vertically with equal spacing.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] Points in *n*-dimensional space are represented as individual polylines with *n* vertices placed on the parallel axes corresponding to each coordinate entry of the *n*-dimensional point, vertices are connected with *n-1* polyline segments.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] This data visualization is similar to time series visualization, except that Parallel Coordinates are applied to data which do not correspond with chronological time.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] Therefore, different axes arrangements can be of interest, including reflecting axes horizontally, otherwise inverting the attribute range.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] The concept of Parallel Coordinates is often said to originate in 1885 by a French mathematician Philbert Maurice d'Ocagne. d'Ocagne sought a way to provide graphical calculation of mathematical functions using alignment diagrams called nomograms which used parallel axes with different scales.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] For example, a three-variable equation could be solved using three parallel axes, marking known values on their scales, then drawing a line between them, with an unknown read from the scale at the point where the line intersects that scale.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] However, both d'Ocagne and Gannet were far preceded in this by André-Michel Guerry, Plate IV, "Influence de l'Age", where he showed rankings of crimes against persons by age along parallel axes, connecting the same crime across age groups.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] Parallel Coordinates were popularised again 87 years later by Alfred Inselberg in 1985 and systematically developed as a coordinate system starting from 1977.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] Some important applications are in collision avoidance algorithms for air traffic control (1987—3 USA patents), data mining (USA patent), computer vision (USA patent), Optimization, process control, more recently in intrusion detection and elsewhere.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] On the plane with an XY Cartesian coordinate system, adding more dimensions in parallel coordinates (often abbreviated ||-coords, PCP, or PC) involves adding more axes.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] The value of parallel coordinates is that certain geometrical properties in high dimensions transform into easily seen 2D patterns.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] For example, a set of points on a line in *n*-space transforms to a set of polylines in parallel coordinates all intersecting at *n* − 1 points.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] For *n* = 2 this yields a point-line duality pointing out why the mathematical foundations of parallel coordinates are developed in the projective rather than Euclidean space.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] A pair of lines intersects at a unique point which has two coordinates and, therefore, can correspond to a unique line which is also specified by two parameters (or two points).
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] In contrast, more than two points are required to specify a curve and also a pair of curves may not have a unique intersection.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] The goal is to map n-dimensional relations into 2D patterns.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] Hence, parallel coordinates is not a point-to-point mapping but rather a *n*D subset to 2D subset mapping, there is no loss of information.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] Note: even a point in nD is not mapped into a point in 2D, but to a polygonal line—a subset of 2D.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] When used for statistical data visualisation there are three important considerations: the order, the rotation, and the scaling of the axes.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] The order of the axes is critical for finding features, and in typical data analysis many reorderings will need to be tried.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] Some authors have come up with ordering heuristics which may create illuminating orderings.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] The rotation of the axes is a translation in the parallel coordinates and if the lines intersected outside the parallel axes it can be translated between them by rotations.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] The simplest example of this is rotating the axis by 180 degrees.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] Scaling is necessary because the plot is based on interpolation (linear combination) of consecutive pairs of variables.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] Therefore, the variables must be in common scale, and there are many scaling methods to be considered as part of data preparation process that can reveal more informative views.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] A smooth parallel coordinate plot is achieved with splines.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] In the smooth plot, every observation is mapped into a parametric line (or curve), which is smooth, continuous on the axes, and orthogonal to each parallel axis.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] This design emphasizes the quantization level for each data attribute.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] Inselberg (Inselberg 1997) made a full review of how to visually read out parallel coordinates relational patterns.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] When most lines between two parallel axes are somewhat parallel to each other, it suggests a positive relationship between these two dimensions.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] When lines cross in a kind of superposition of X-shapes, it's a negative relationship.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] When lines cross randomly or are parallel, it shows there is no particular relationship.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] In parallel coordinates, each axis can have at most two neighboring axes (one on the left, and one on the right).
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] For a *n*-dimensional data set, at most *n*-1 relationships can be shown at a time without altering the approach.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] In time series visualization, there exists a natural predecessor and successor; therefore in this special case, there exists a preferred arrangement.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] However, when the axes do not have a unique order, finding a good axis arrangement requires the use of experimentation and feature engineering.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] To explore more relationships, axes may be reordered or restructured.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] One approach arranges axes in 3-dimensional space (still in parallel, forming a Lattice graph), an axis can have more than two neighbors in a circle around the central attribute, and the arrangement problem can be improve by using a minimum spanning tree.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] A prototype of this visualization is available as extension to the data mining software ELKI.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] However, the visualization is harder to interpret and interact with than a linear order.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] While there are a large number of papers about parallel coordinates, there are only a few notable software publicly available to convert databases into parallel coordinates graphics.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] Notable software are ELKI, GGobi, Mondrian, and ROOT.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] Libraries include Protovis.js, D3.js provides basic examples.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] D3.Parcoords.js (a D3-based library) specifically dedicated to parallel coordinates graphic creation has also been published.
[src:parallel-coordinates/parallel-coordinates] The Python data structure and analysis library Pandas implements parallel coordinates plotting, using the plotting library matplotlib.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] A **radar chart** is a graphical method of displaying multivariate data in the form of a two-dimensional chart of three or more quantitative variables represented on axes starting from the same point.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Radar charts are also known as **web charts**, **spider charts**, **spider graphs**, **spider web charts**, **star charts**, **star plots**, **cobweb charts**, **irregular polygons**, **polar charts**, and **Kiviat diagrams**.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] It is equivalent to a parallel coordinates plot, with the axes arranged radially.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] The radar chart is a chart and/or plot that consists of a sequence of equi-angular spokes, called radii, with each spoke representing one of the variables.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] The data length of a spoke is proportional to the magnitude of the variable for the data point relative to the maximum magnitude of the variable across all data points.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] A line is drawn connecting the data values for each spoke.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] This gives the plot a star-like appearance and the origin of one of the popular names for this plot.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Radar charts are a useful way to display multivariate observations with an arbitrary number of variables.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Each star represents a single observation.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Typically, radar charts are generated in a multi-plot format with many stars on each page and each star representing one observation.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] The star plot was first used by Georg von Mayr in 1877.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Radar charts differ from glyph plots in that all variables are used to construct the plotted star figure.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] There is no separation into foreground and background variables.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Instead, the star-shaped figures are usually arranged in a rectangular array on the page.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] It is somewhat easier to see patterns in the data if the observations are arranged in some non-arbitrary order (if the variables are assigned to the rays of the star in some meaningful order).
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Radar charts can be used in sports to chart players' strengths and weaknesses by calculating various statistics related to the player that can tracked along the central axis of the chart.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Examples include a basketball players shots made, rebounds, assists, etc., or the batting or pitching stats of a baseball player.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] This creates a centralized visualization of the strengths and weaknesses of a player, and if overlapped with the statistics of other players or league averages, can display where a player excels and where they could improve.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] These insights into player strengths and weakness could prove crucial to player development as it allows coaches and trainers to adjust a player's training regiment to help improve on their weaknesses.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] The results of the radar chart can also be useful in situational play.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] If a batter is shown to hit poorly against left-handed pitching, then his team knows to limit his plate appearances against left-handed pitchers, while the opposing team may try to force a situation where the batter is forced to hit against the pitcher.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Another application of radar charts is the control of quality improvement to display the performance metrics various objects including computer programs, computers, phones, vehicles, and more.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Computer programmer often use analytics to test the performance of their programs versus others.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] An example of this where radar charts may be useful is the performance analysis of various sorting algorithms.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Another performance application is measuring the performance of similar cars against each other.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] A consumer could look at variables such as the cars' top speed, miles per gallon, horsepower, and torque.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Then after using a radar chart to visualize the data, they could decide on what car is best for them based on the results.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Radar charts can be used in life sciences to display the strengths and weakness of drugs and other medications.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Using the example of two anti-depressants, a researcher can rank variables such as efficacy, side effects, cost, etc. on a scale of one to ten.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] They could then graph the results using a radar chart to see the spread of variables and find how the differ, such as one anti-depressant being cheaper and quicker acting, but not having great relief over time.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Meanwhile, the other anti-depressant provides stronger relief and holds up better over time but is more expensive.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Another life science application is in patient analysis.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Radar charts can be used to graph the variables of life affecting a person's wellness, and then be analyzed to help them.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] A more specific example is in the case of athletes, whose various wellness habits such as sleep, diet, and stress are monitored to make sure they stay in peak physical condition.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] If any areas would be shown dipping, doctors and trainers could step in to assist the athlete and improve their wellness.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Radar charts are primarily suited for strikingly showing *outliers* and *commonality*, or when one chart is greater in every variable than another, and primarily used for ordinal measurements where each variable corresponds to "better" in some respect and all variables are on the same scale.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Conversely, radar charts have been criticized as poorly suited for making trade-off decisions when one chart is greater than another on some variables, but less on others.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Further, it is hard to visually compare lengths of different spokes, because radial distances are hard to judge, though concentric circles help as grid lines.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Instead, one may use a simple line graph, particularly for a time series.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Radar charts can distort data to some extent, especially when areas are filled in, because the area contained becomes proportional to the square of the linear measures.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] For example, in a chart with 5 variables that range from 1 to 100, the area contained by the polygon bounded by 5 points when all measures are 90 is more than 10% larger than the same for a chart with all values of 82.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Radar charts can also become hard to visually compare between different samples on the chart when their values are close as their lines or areas bleed into each other, as shown in Figure 5.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] For example, the alternating data 9, 1, 9, 1, 9, 1 yields a spiking radar chart (which goes in and out), while reordering the data as 9, 9, 9, 1, 1, 1 instead yields two distinct wedges (sectors).
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] In some cases there is a natural structure, and radar charts can be well-suited.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] For example, for diagrams of data that vary over a 24-hour cycle, each hour's data is naturally related to its neighbor and the overall data has a cyclic structure, so it can naturally be displayed as a radar chart.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Radar charts are helpful for small-to-moderate-sized multivariate data sets.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Their primary weakness is that their effectiveness is limited to data sets with less than a few hundred points.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] After that, they tend to be overwhelming.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Further, when using radar charts with multiple dimensions or samples, the radar chart may become cluttered and harder to interpret as the number of samples grows.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] For example, take the batting stats table comparing MLB 2021 MVP Shohei Ohtani, vs the stats of the leagues average designated hitters and some Hall of Fame players.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] These stats represent the percentage of hits, home runs, strike outs, etc. per at bat of a player.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] For more information on what each stat used in the table represents, you can refer to this reference by the MLB.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] We will use this table below to create Radar charts comparing the 2021 MVP batting stats to the league averages for Designated Hitters and regular batters, in an attempt to visualize performance metrics and visually come to a conclusion that Shohei out performed the average player.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Next we will include additional samples into the Radar chart, using Hall of Fame players Jackie Robinson, Jim Thome, and Frank Thomas to compare Shohei to a few of the greatest batters of all time.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] This Radar chart not only can give us intuition of how Shohei compares to the top historical players, but will also serve a purpose in showing the limitations of having too many samples in a Radar chart.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] We can see in Figure 10 how a radar chart can be easily interpreted when the number of spokes and samples is relatively small.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] When we compare more samples in Figure 11, even without an area fill on the radar chart, it becomes apparent how difficult it can become to interpret or make trade-off decisions.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] The chart on the right contains the star plots of 15 cars.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] We can look at these plots individually or we can use them to identify clusters of cars with similar features.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] For example, we can look at the star plot of the Cadillac Seville (the last one on the image) and see that it is one of the most expensive cars, gets below average (but not among the worst) gas mileage, has an average repair record, and has average-to-above-average roominess and size.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] We can then compare the Cadillac models (the last three plots) with the AMC models (the first three plots).
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] This comparison shows distinct patterns.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] The AMC models tend to be inexpensive, have below average gas mileage, and are small in both height and weight and in roominess.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] The Cadillac models are expensive, have poor gas mileage, and are large in both size and roominess.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] One may use line graphs for time series and other data, in the form of parallel coordinates.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] For graphical qualitative comparison of 2-dimensional tabular data in several variables, a common alternative are Harvey balls, which are used extensively by *Consumer Reports*.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Comparison in Harvey balls (and radar charts) may be significantly aided by ordering the variables algorithmically to add order.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] An excellent way for visualising structures within multivariate data is offered by principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Another alternative is to use small, inline bar charts, which may be compared to sparklines.
[src:parallel-coordinates/star-plot] Although radar and polar charts are often described as the same chart types, some sources make a difference between them and even consider the radar chart to be a polar chart's variation that does not display data in terms of polar coordinate.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] A **visual variable**, in cartographic design, graphic design, and data visualization, is an aspect of a graphical object that can visually differentiate it from other objects, and can be controlled during the design process.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Graphic techniques have been used in maps and statistical charts to represent non-visual information since the 17th Century, and information visualization blossomed in the 19th Century, highlighted by the work of William Playfair and Charles Joseph Minard.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] However, the direct study of this abstract use of graphical appearance began with the emergence of cartography as an academic research discipline in the mid-20th Century.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] In *The Look of Maps* (1952), often considered the genesis of American cartographic theory, Arthur H.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Robinson discussed the role of size, shape, and color in establishing contrast in maps.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] At the same time in France, Jacques Bertin published an early version of his list of visual variables: shape, value, and "sparkling" (grain).
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Robinson, in his 1960 *Elements of Cartography*, which quickly became the dominant textbook on the subject, discussed size, shape, color, and pattern as the qualities of map symbols that establish contrast and represent geographic information.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Bertin was a cartographer at the École pratique des hautes études (EPHE) in Paris, where he created maps and graphics for faculty from various disciplines using a wide variety of data.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Despite having a background in cartography, and deriving many of his ideas by evaluating maps, he intended for *Sémiologie Graphique* to be applied to all forms of graphic design and information visualization.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Soon the idea was gaining international acceptance; in 1974 Joel Morrison presented a very similar system in the context of cartographic generalization, citing neither Bertin nor Robinson but saying that it was a "traditional categorization," suggesting its widespread nature by that point.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Despite the title of Bertin's work, it actually contained little reference to the scientific knowledge in the field of Semiotics or any other, and was primarily a practical summation of patterns he found in practice.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] The "truth" of the visual variables concept was largely established by its widespread and long-lasting acceptance.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] The earliest lists commonly suggested six variables: location size, shape, value, hue, orientation, and grain (pattern spacing).
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] To this list, several additions have been suggested, with a few entering the canonical lists found in textbooks, while other suggestions have largely been dropped in cartography.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] With the rise of multimedia as a cartographic tool, analogous sets of non-visual communication variables have also been presented.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Starting with Robinson and Bertin, a core set of visual variables has become largely canonical, appearing in cartography and information visualization textbooks, and built into most design software in some form.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] The size of a symbol is how much space it occupies.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] This commonly refers to the area of point symbols, and the thickness of line symbols.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Size differences are relatively easy to recognize, making it a useful variable to convey information, such as a quantitative amount of something, or relative importance.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Studies have shown that humans are better at judging relative differences in linear distance (e.g. one road being twice as thick as another) than relative differences in area (e.g., one circle having twice the area of another).
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Such estimations are the most accurate from squares.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Area differences of circles are generally underestimated, but there is a large variation between people in ability to estimate two-dimensional size.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Correctly estimating relative volume has proven even more difficult.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Because geographical features have an actual size on the Earth, this cannot always be controlled, and sometimes works against the wishes of a cartographer; for example, it can be difficult to make a world map in which Russia does not stand out.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] In a cartogram the size of features is purposefully distorted to represent a variable other than area.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] A shape is a simple design that is used to symbolize an attribute on a map.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Shape is most commonly attached to point features in maps.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Some shapes are simple in nature and thus are more abstract, while other shapes are more pictorial and are easy for the reader to comprehend what is trying to be conveyed.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Some aspects of shape are inherent to the phenomenon and may not be easily manipulable, especially in line and region symbols, such as the shape of a road or a country.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] However, shape can still play a role in line and region symbols, such as a region filled with tree symbols or an arrowhead on a line.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Also, the shape of a feature may be purposefully distorted by Cartographic generalization, especially when creating schematic representations such as many transit maps, although this distortion is rarely used to convey information, only to reduce emphasis on shape and location.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] As an aspect of color, **value** refers to how light or dark an object appears.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Value effectively connotes "more" and "less," an ordinal measure; this makes it a very useful form of symbology in thematic maps, especially choropleth maps.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Value contributes strongly to Visual hierarchy; elements that contrast most with the value of the background tend to stand out most (e.g., black on a white sheet of paper, white on a black computer screen).
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] The **saturation** of a color is its purity or intensity, created by the variety of light composing it; a single wavelength of light is of the highest saturation, while white, black, or gray has no saturation (being an even mixture of all visible wavelengths).
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Of the three psychological aspects of color, this is the least effective at conveying specific information, but it is very effective at establishing figure-ground and visual hierarchy, with bright colors generally standing out more than muted tones or shades of gray.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Bertin mentions saturation in his discussion of "color" (hue), but did not include it as a distinct variable.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Orientation refers to the direction labels and symbols are facing on a map (occasionally called "direction" or "angle").
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Although it is not used as often as many of the other visual variables, it can be useful for communicating information about the real-world orientation of features.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Common examples include wind direction and the direction in which a spring flows.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Although terminology for this aspect still varies somewhat today, *texture* or *pattern* in this context generally refers to an aggregate symbol composed of recurring sub-symbols.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] This can include areas (such as a forest filled with small tree point symbols) and line symbols (such as a railroad with recurring cross-hatches).
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] The amount of white space between the sub-symbols in the pattern.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Bertin's French term *grain* was translated as "texture" in the 1983 English edition, and appeared frequently as such in subsequent lists, but others have suggested that *granularity* or just *grain* is a better translation.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] The orderliness of the location of the sub-symbols in the pattern, generally either regularly spaced in rows and columns (often indicating a human construction, such as an orchard), or randomly spaced (often indicating a natural distribution).
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] A number of additional variables have been suggested at times.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Some are recent technology-driven proposals, while others are earlier entries that have fallen out of favor.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] The absolute location of the symbol in the design, specified as (x,y) coordinates.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] This was a core part of Bertin's model, who distinguished these "imposition variables" from the other "retinal variables." This has largely been dropped from most subsequent lists by cartographers, since location in a map is predetermined by geography.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] However, it is crucial for representing information in charts and other data visualizations; for example, position is the main method of visualizing quantitative values in a scatterplot.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Even in cartography, position becomes a variable when labeling and laying out the non-map elements on the page.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] It is also relevant when representing fields; for example, the location of an isoline is an abstract visualization of a property, not the location of a real-world linear feature.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] In a regular arrangement, the direction in which the sub-symbols are arrayed.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Bertin considered this just the area version of the primary variable of orientation, but Morrison included it as a separate variable, likely because the orientation of the individual sub-symbols may be different than the angle in which they are arranged.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] In recent years, it has rarely been included, likely due to the overall decrease in the use of fill patterns in the era of digital cartography.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] These corollary terms refer to the degree to which a symbol blends with other symbols at the same location, giving the illusion of the symbol in front being translucent.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] A fairly recent addition, the control of opacity has become common in digital cartography.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] While it is rarely used to convey specific information, it is effective for reducing contrast or to retain underlying information.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Despite its widespread use, it is rarely mentioned in textbooks.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] This is the degree to which a symbol is drawn with crisp or fuzzy edges.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Briefly mentioned in the *Elements* textbook in 1978, the concept was more fully developed by Alan MacEachren in 1992 as a tool for representing locational uncertainty; he first called it *focus*, then chose *crispness*, which has been the most common term in subsequent lists.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] This is the technique of purposefully pixelating a symbol or feature as a way of generalizing and obscuring it, usually for communicating some form of uncertainty about the feature.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] This was also first introduced in that context by MacEachren, but is not commonly used, and has rarely been mentioned since.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] By extension, this can also refer to the general level of detail in a symbol, which is used more often than pixelation, especially in the context of cartographic generalization.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] On three-dimensional perspective maps, it is common to extrude shapes in the z direction, so that height represents a property.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] According to Bertin, each of the visual variables suggests its own mode of perception and interpretation, which MacEachren ties to the cognitive theory of Image schema (e.g., size: Large-small ~ more-less).
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] These modes make each variable better for representing certain kinds of information, and serving certain purposes, than others.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Specifically, Bertin introduces four properties of these variables, which tie them directly to their role in the visual hierarchy and to their ability to represent data in each of Steven's levels of measurement.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Each of these variables may be employed to convey information, to provide contrast between different features and layers, to establish figure-ground contrast and a clear visual hierarchy, or add to the aesthetic appeal of the map.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Map symbols commonly employ multiple visual variables simultaneously.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] This can be used to reinforce the depiction of a single property; for example, a capital city having a symbol that is larger and a different shape than other cities, or a color progression on a choropleth map from pale yellow to dark green, using both hue and value.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Alternatively, different visual variables may be used to represent different properties; for example, symbols for cities may be differentiated by size to indicate population, and by shape to indicate provincial and national capitals.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] Some visual variable can be combined harmoniously to make a map clearer and more informative, while other combinations tend to add more confusion than usefulness.
[src:parallel-coordinates/visual-variable] For example, early experiments with using Chernoff faces on maps have been criticized as difficult to interpret correctly.
